                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d401">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/965: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-21T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 21, 1937—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your September 18, noon, paragraph 5. The suggestion which you made to
                    representatives of several mission societies is in substantial accord with
                    instructions issued by a number of mission boards to their organizations in
                    China in response to the Department’s letters to the International Missionary
                    Council and the National Catholic Welfare Conference, copies of which were sent
                    by those organizations respectively to all Protestant Mission Boards and to all
                    Catholic religious communities in the United States having workers in China.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
